{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.74,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48942"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33942"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"1218"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48942"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with worsening leg ulcers. She has a history of ileo-colic Crohn\u0027s disease diagnosed at age six. For the past two months, she has developed painful ulcerated lesions on her legs that have been rapidly progressing. Her current medications include sulfasalazine and azathioprine. She has no significant travel history. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her height and weight are at the 25th percentile for her age. Inspection of her legs reveals multiple deep, painful ulcers with violaceous, undermined borders (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Necrotising fasciitis","Venous stasis ulcers","Pyoderma gangrenosum","Cutaneous leishmaniasis","Ecthyma gangrenosum"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Epyoderma gangrenosum\u003C/strong\u003E. This rare, inflammatory skin condition is characterised by painful, rapidly progressing ulcers with violaceous, undermined borders, which match the description and image provided. The association with Crohn\u0027s disease, especially in a paediatric patient, further supports this diagnosis. Pyoderma gangrenosum is considered an extra-intestinal manifestation of inflammatory bowel disease, particularly Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotising fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rapidly progressing bacterial infection of the deep fascia. While it can cause skin ulceration, it typically presents with severe pain, systemic toxicity, and rapid spread, which are not described in this case. The patient appears well, which is inconsistent with necrotising fasciitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous stasis ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E are uncommon in children and typically occur in the context of chronic venous insufficiency. They usually appear on the medial aspect of the lower leg and ankle, and do not have the characteristic violaceous, undermined borders seen in pyoderma gangrenosum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous leishmaniasis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by parasites transmitted by sandflies. While it can cause skin ulcers, these typically develop at the site of the sandfly bite and are usually singular. The lack of travel history and the association with Crohn\u0027s disease make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcthyma gangrenosum\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa \u003C/em\u003Esepticaemia in immunocompromised patients. It usually presents as painless, round, erythematous macules that rapidly become pustular and then necrotic. The patient\u0027s well appearance and the chronic nature of the lesions make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyoderma gangrenosum is a rare, inflammatory skin condition that can be associated with inflammatory bowel disease, particularly Crohn\u0027s disease in children.","Pyoderma gangrenosum typically presents as painful, rapidly progressing ulcers with violaceous, undermined borders."],"references":["Schadt C. Pyoderma gangrenosum: Pathogenesis, clinical features, and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024; Retrieved 2024 Jun 28. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/pyoderma-gangrenosum-pathogenesis-clinical-features-and-diagnosis?search=Pyoderma%20gangrenosum\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1%7E92\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","George C, Deroide F, Rustin M. Pyoderma gangrenosum - a guide to diagnosis and management\u2002. Clin Med (Lond). 2019 May;19(3):224-228. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6542232/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33942"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13804"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20747"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20747"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D7r3Lew9Ow27ilJfoCe0pFO5X3y8g6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D7r3Lew9O